There was a group essay, quizzes, a midterm, and a final. I find that the course has interesting material that is easy to understand as long as you adequately study it. Dr. Deuboue is a great professor!
Makes concepts way to complicated hard to understand just bad in general
This class was really BAD, the PPTs had too many slides and u had to memorize so many things. The questions on the exams were the worst thing, they were ultra tricky. I'd say avoid him...

I loved this prof. He was just a nice guy. I can't really say he taught. You took notes on the readings from the textbook, but I got by on his slides bc thats what he tests on. You take notes, attend his zoom which is just a q&a, and then he releases a 10q quiz you take in 4 minutes. The exams were easy and straight forward. Easy class.

He requires 5 business days to answer emails but only left 4 business days between when he would put up the reading for the week and when the next quiz was, and took full advantage of this. He was rude and aggressive when asked questions. His tests were ambiguous in their wording and very picky on details and statistics. Lots of people dropped it.

AVOID AT ALL COSTS! Had this prof online due to the pandemic. Gave us a quiz every week with 10 questions to do in 4 minutes (2,5%). After a lot of complaints, gradually changed it to 8 minutes. Quiz/midterm are way to specific. Lots of stat questions. Too many slides that are repetitive and unnecessary. Take this with another prof if you can.

AVOID AT ALL COSTS! Had him during pandemic/online. Gave a quiz every week worth 2,5%, 10 questions for 4 minutes at first and after lots of complaints, gradually went up to 8 minutes. Puts lots of stats questions and some that are way too specific. Too many slides that I find are repetitive and unnecessary. Take this with another prof if you can.

I was surprised this prof had so many bad reviews! I honestly enjoyed his class. The things we went over were really interesting! Would take a class with him again
Too much slides for a 10 question quiz. Gives unreasonable times for mid terms (under an hour) for 50 questions. Does not answer his emails and has no pity for students :(

rComments: Be careful: - Use his PPT and copy word for word (quizzes have T/F questions where he changes one word of a definition which makes it false) - Study graphs and statistics (even if he doesnt really go over them in class, and even if they are about other countries, make sure you know them) - DO NOT SKIP a quiz or you wont pass Good luck ��

Worst prof ever. Extremely dry and also very hard to understand as he has a heavy accent. Always stated in lectures that we didn't need to know stats, and then he made 25% of the final stats. Rude and passive aggressive.

As a french immersion student, his lectures were really hard to understand so everything he said went right over my head. I stopped attending class altogether. The class itself is pretty much common sense, so don't worry too much about the prof. Exams were a little challenging, but fair if you know the material. Prof is nice enough, just boring.
Extremely disorganized!!!! Slides are SO boring, the exam questions are extremely difficult and filled with grammar mistakes.

You can survive off the textbooks and slides. Exam questions seem easy and upfront but he likes to trick you so pay attention to details. His lectures are very monotone and he reads off the slides. So disappointed by my experience with this prof. Great prof!

Boring teacher. Midterms are uniquely based on his PowerPoint. Not that much material. Told us are midterm was not cumulative and it turned out to be. Doesn't take any pity for his students. Clearly doesn't revise his exams, had to remove 25 questions from our final.

I went to class a total of 3 times ! Just teach yourself. I went over his slides and read the textbook and that was enough for me to get good enough marks. If you are French immersion *avoid at all costs* you won't be able to understand him and going to his class are useless anyway bc he reads off the power points. rComments: Material was common sense. He read off the slides and posted them a few days after, so attending class was not necessary. Kind of hard to understand him at times because of his thick accent and monotone voice, you had to really listen to what he was saying. To be fair it was his first term teaching and I believe he means well. However, our midterms were only 25 MCQ which makes you feel like you studied 4 chapters for nothing as it's pretty much a gamble what will be evaluated. It also meant each question counted for 1% of your final mark! Class not necessary to attend as he just reads off the slides
